{#- DEFINITION — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="6150-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">Error 6150, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Error 6150, -1006 appears when QuickBooks Desktop tries to open or create a company file and the file is damaged, is the wrong file type, or can&rsquo;t be accessed. You most often see it when the working company (.QBW) file has been damaged, when malware or antivirus quarantined or corrupted the file, or when someone tries to open a backup (.QBB) or portable (.QBM) file directly as if it were a .QBW &mdash; those files must be restored properly first, not opened in place. The error is QuickBooks telling you it reached for a file it expected to be a healthy company file and found one it can&rsquo;t open or build.</p>
      <p>The good news is that Error 6150 is often fixable, and the self-fix steps below work in order of likelihood &mdash; running QuickBooks Tool Hub (Quick Fix My File, then File Doctor) resolves it in many cases before deeper troubleshooting is needed. If self-fix doesn&rsquo;t resolve it, the file is genuinely damaged, or malware is involved, a Certified ProAdvisor diagnostic identifies the deeper cause &mdash; typically file-integrity damage or a data-recovery situation past the documented surface steps. Error 6150 is a QuickBooks Desktop and Enterprise error; it does not appear in QuickBooks Online.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

